title: For Sale:  Ruger MkIII 22/45 5.5" Bull Barrel
postcontent:
I set this up for target shooting, but I haven't had the time and bills need to be paid.  The round count is under 400, I ended up customizing the gun more than I actually got to take it out.  Looking for $400 OBO for everything.

Here is the setup for sale:

- Ruger MkIII Blued 5.5" Bull Barrel w/Adjustable Sights, original case and manual with a custom 1911 Hogue Grip installed (details on this below)
- Sight Rib installed
- Tasco Silver ProPoint Red Dot (some wear, glass is perfect)
- 3 Magazines
- McFadden Ultimate Cliploader
- Box of CCI Mini Mag (100)

Details on the grip:
The earlier series of the Ruger MkIII 22/45 had a molded grip that is just too thin and uncomfortable (anyone that has these knows what I'm talking about), and there was no way to use aftermarket grips.  

People have tmade aftermarket grips in the following ways:

1. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BRkiSlXdrKM) which require drilling into the frame, or

2. http://www.perfectunion.com/vb/guns-guns-guns/68671-ruger-22-45-modded.html, techniques that require milling and grinding the frame down to accept standard 1911 grips.  

I wanted to do neither, so looking at the various techniques I was able to fabricate a Hogue 1911 wrap around grip (modifying the grip, not the gun), and adhering it with industrial strength silicone adhesive.  It works perfectly, preserves the original gun, and feels as these grips would on a 1911, so this is somewhat unique and a process figured out DIY.  The feel, grip angle and recoil reduction (what little there is to begin with) is excellent.  I personally felt Hogue slip over grips felt terrible and affected the balance and grip angle substantially.  Obviously this will be a matter of preference, but they are easily removed.  

To remove the grip, all it takes is peeling the grip off (with some substantial effort), and rubbing away, brushing out with a cleaning brush the silicone that remains, and restoring the gun back to original factory grip.  

So this is a very unique setup, and it was my primary target pistol until I upgraded to a true 1911 22 dedicated setup.

Email with questions.  Not really looking for trades unless it's a S&W .38 or .357 revolver.

title: For Sale:  Colt 380 Mk IV (700.00 obo)
location: Allentown, Pa & Chadds Ford, Pa, Southeastern, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
Used colt .380 MK IV Series.

I bought this gun from a gun store in Chadds Ford Pa., about a month ago. The condition is very good for the age of the gun. I would say 97% perfect. I bought this gun as an investment but reconsidered and now I would rather use the money to continue adding onto my AR15's. I paid 699.99 plus tax so around 740.00 out the door. I listed a description below of the colt MK IV gun from a website I found. I can send as many pictures are you would like to an email.

Also, I had the store send the gun out to colt to check for functionality and safety. It just came back on 10/9/11 in perfect working order. 

Buyer must pay transfer fees.

Comes with box and 1 magazine

Description 


This Colt Mk IV Series 80 Government Model was manufactured in 1984 according to the company records. It is a self-loading, recoil operated, semi-automatic pistol that is chambered for the .380 ACP cartridge. The pistol has been designed to operate as a single action firearm that utilizes an external hammer and a locked breech. The Patridge sights includes a blade front sight and a square notch rear sight that is drift adjustable for windage only. The Mk IV is fed by a single column 7 round detachable box magazine. The pistol utilizes a push button magazine release located on the left side of the receiver in front of the grip. The manual thumb safety is located behind the left grip and must be in the fire position before the slide is allowed to move rearward. The pistol has a 3 1/4 inch barrel and an overall length of 6.15 inches and an unloaded weight of 21 3/4 ounces. This firearm does employ a slide hold open mechanism to inform the operator that the last round has been fired. The finish is a deep Colt blue. The checkered grip panels are a cream colored plastic and sport a gold Colt logo with the famous rampant Colt symbol in the middle of each grip. The trigger and recoil spring guide are made of plastic.

The Colt Mk IV Series 80 Government Model chambered in .380 ACP caliber was in production from 1984 to 1997.

The .380 Automatic Colt Pistol cartridge has a bullet diameter of .355 inches and was first introduced by Colt in 1908. It is also known as the 9mm Short, 9mm Browning, 9mm Kurz, 9mm Corto and 9x17mm.  The cartridge was originally designed for the early blowback pistols that lacked a barrel locking mechanism commonly known as a locked breech design. The .380 ACP round travels at a rate of about 1000 feet per second and with a 90 to 95 grain projectile, it can deliver between 200 and 205 foot pounds of energy at the muzzle. For comparison, a .38 special round travels at a rate of around 980 feet per second and with a 110 grain projectile it can produce around 235 foot pounds of muzzle energy. Which makes the .38 special slightly more powerful than the .380 ACP round.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Egyptian Hakim
postcontent:
I have an Egyptian Hakim in 8mm it's a neat but different rifle I'm looking to sell or trade The Hakim Rifle (70,000 produced) is an accurate, reliable, gas operated semi-automatic rifle. It was originally designed by the Swedes and produced as the AG-42 Ljungman for the Swedish Army. The tooling and design were later sold to the United Arab Republic (Egypt), and the Hakim was produced there during the 1950's and 60's. The adjustable gas operated system is very simple and is not unlike the U.S. M16 rifle.

The Hakim features the proven and very strong tipping bolt system like the FN49, Russian SKS and French MAS56 rifles. Available in 8 mm Mauser caliber, 192 grain (12 g) bullet only, it is a finely machined (expensive to produce), sturdy semi-automatic rifle of the highest quality. The Hakim has a removable 10 round magazine intended to be reloaded with 5 round stripper clips (8 mm Mauser).

title: For Sale:  1977 Cadillac Coupe DeVille
location: New Albany, southern IN., Indiana, United States
postcontent:
This is not just some 35 year old car thats been sitting in a garage uncared for.  I have put over $4500 in this classic beauty in the last three years I have owned it.  This Coupe has over $3000 in body and paint work that I had done as soon as I purchased the car.  I am not new to Cadillacs nor older large frame cars and I purchased this car vecause the 424 cubic inch big block engine ran outstanding and the frame was rock solid.  The Landau or mock convertible top was totally ratted out when I purchased the car.  The biggest problem cosmeticly was where the top met the body rust had began to rat holes clear through.  When I took the Cadillac to Spray Shop Customs the body shop owner explained that for around $1700 he could use body filler and Bondo on the rust and it would look good for a few years.  Or if I intended on keeping the car he could do it the right way which meant cutting out any rusty areas, welding in new metal, sanding it smooth and then paint for a permanent repair. I opted for the job done correctly.  The top is new.

The transmission was replaced with brand new last year to the tune of $1000 at Tuckers in Clarksville.  This tranny shop has a great reputation for good work.  The title says 167,000 miles thats saying the odometer rolled at some point.  I believe this is a mistake and someone who titled the car before me made the assumption that the odometer had rolled over so thats what it says on title.  My point is that the engine doesnt leek oil, and runs too well for that many miles.  The interior is kind of rough as I hadnt got to that yet.  The a/c and heat need work because when you kick them on the belt squeels.  The car needs some minor things like that, but is ready to drive anywhere.
THE PRICE IS OBO
I will be taking a pretty big hit on this car at this price, but I know times are tight and I am pricing it to sell.  I may take partial trades on firearms, but dont offer me another car.  I drive a Volvo wagon as my daily driver, this has been my cruising on Sunday ride.
